content:
Here's a complete single-page HTML analog clock app in one Markdown code block:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Analog Clock</title>
  <style>
    body {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      height: 100vh;
      margin: 0;
      background: #f0f0f0;
    }
    .clock {
      width: 300px;
      height: 300px;
      border: 10px solid #333;
      border-radius: 50%;
      position: relative;
      background: white;
      box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
    }
    .clock-face {
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      position: relative;
    }
    .hand {
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      transform-origin: 50% 100%;
      border-radius: 5px;
      z-index: 2;
    }
    .hour-hand {
      width: 8px;
      height: 80px;
      background: #333;
      margin-left: -4px;
    }
    .minute-hand {
      width: 5px;
      height: 120px;
      background: #555;
      margin-left: -2.5px;
    }
    .second-hand {
      width: 2px;
      height: 130px;
      background: #f00;
      margin-left: -1px;
    }
    .center-dot {
      position: absolute;
      top: 50%;
      left: 50%;
      width: 16px;
      height: 16px;
      background: #f00;
      border-radius: 50%;
      margin: -8px 0 0 -8px;
      z-index: 3;
    }
    .number {
      position: absolute;
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      text-align: center;
      font-size: 20px;
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      font-weight: bold;
    }
    .number div {
      position: absolute;
    }
    /* Position numbers around the clock */
    .twelve { transform: translate(-50%, 10px); left: 50%; top: 0; }
    .one { right: 70px; top: 20px; }
    .two { right: 30px; top: 60px; }
    .three { right: 10px; top: 50%; transform: translateY(-50%); }
    .four { right: 30px; bottom: 60px; }
    .five { right: 70px; bottom: 20px; }
    .six { left: 50%; bottom: 10px; transform: translateX(-50%); }
    .seven { left: 70px; bottom: 20px; }
    .eight { left: 30px; bottom: 60px; }
    .nine { left: 10px; top: 50%; transform: translateY(-50%); }
    .ten { left: 30px; top: 60px; }
    .eleven { left: 70px; top: 20px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div class="clock">
    <div class="clock-face">
      <div class="hand hour-hand"></div>
      <div class="hand minute-hand"></div>
      <div class="hand second-hand"></div>
      <div class="center-dot"></div>
      <div class="number">
        <div class="twelve">12</div>
        <div class="one">1</div>
        <div class="two">2</div>
        <div class="three">3</div>
        <div class="four">4</div>
        <div class="five">5</div>
        <div class="six">6</div>
        <div class="seven">7</div>
        <div class="eight">8</div>
        <div class="nine">9</div>
        <div class="ten">10</div>
        <div class="eleven">11</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    function updateClock() {
      const now = new Date();
      const seconds = now.getSeconds();
      const minutes = now.getMinutes();
      const hours = now.getHours() % 12;

      // Calculate degrees for each hand
      const secondDegrees = ((seconds / 60) * 360) + 90;
      const minuteDegrees = ((minutes / 60) * 360) + ((seconds / 60) * 6) + 90;
      const hourDegrees = ((hours / 12) * 360) + ((minutes / 60) * 30) + 90;

      // Apply rotation
      document.querySelector('.second-hand').style.transform = `rotate(${secondDegrees}deg)`;
      document.querySelector('.minute-hand').style.transform = `rotate(${minuteDegrees}deg)`;
      document.querySelector('.hour-hand').style.transform = `rotate(${hourDegrees}deg)`;
    }

    // Update immediately and then every second
    updateClock();
    setInterval(updateClock, 1000);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This HTML file contains:
1. A styled analog clock face with numbers 1-12
2. Three clock hands (hour, minute, second)
3. JavaScript that updates the clock hands every second
4. Smooth CSS transitions for the hands
5. Proper positioning of all clock elements
6. A red center dot and second hand for visibility

Just copy this entire block into an HTML file and open it in any modern browser to see it working.

Here's an enhanced version of the analog clock with improved styling, animations, and visual appeal:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Elegant Analog Clock</title>
  <style>
    @import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Montserrat:wght@400;700&display=swap');

    body {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      align-items: center;
      height: 100vh;
      margin: 0;
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, #667eea 0%, #764ba2 100%);
      font-family: 'Montserrat', sans-serif;
      overflow: hidden;
    }

    .clock-container {
      position: relative;
      filter: drop-shadow(0 0 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.3));
    }

    .clock {
      width: 350px;
      height: 350px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      position: relative;
      background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.9);
      box-shadow: 
        inset 0 0 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.1),
        0 20px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
      backdrop-filter: blur(5px);
    }

    .clock::before {
      content: '';
      position: absolute;
      width: 93%;
      height: 93%;
      border-radius: 50%;
